title: "Down with Dirac Delta"
---
Many texts in physics naively define the Dirac delta function $\delta:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$ as

$$ \delta(x)=\begin{cases} &\infty,\text{ if }x=0\\ &0\text{ if }x\neq0 \end{cases}. $$

However, $\infty\notin\mathbb{R}$, so this rule does not defines a function properly. To remedy this, many texts, such as Butkov, states that the Dirac delta must be thought as the limit of a sequence of functions. Such sequences are called as $\emph{delta sequences}$. For instance, consider the sequence $(f_n)$ of functions $f_n:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$ given by

$$ f_n(x)=\frac{n}{\sqrt{\pi}}e^{-n^2x^2}. $$
